# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: chisel-hdl
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:chisel-hdl/chisel-programming-language] Chisel is based on Scala as a domain-specific language (DSL).
[src:chisel-hdl/chisel-programming-language] Chisel inherits the object-oriented and functional programming aspects of Scala for describing digital hardware.
[src:chisel-hdl/chisel-programming-language] Using Scala as a basis allows describing circuit generators.
[src:chisel-hdl/chisel-programming-language] High quality, free access documentation exists in several languages.
[src:chisel-hdl/chisel-programming-language] Circuits described in Chisel can be converted to a description in Verilog for synthesis and simulation.
[src:chisel-hdl/chisel-programming-language] Although Chisel is not yet a mainstream hardware description language, it has been explored by several companies and institutions.
[src:chisel-hdl/chisel-programming-language] The most prominent use of Chisel is an implementation of the RISC-V instruction set, the open-source Rocket chip.
[src:chisel-hdl/chisel-programming-language] Chisel is mentioned by the Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency (DARPA) as a technology to improve the efficiency of electronic design, where smaller design teams do larger designs.
[src:chisel-hdl/chisel-programming-language] Google has used Chisel to develop a Tensor Processing Unit for edge computing.
[src:chisel-hdl/chisel-programming-language] Some developers prefer Chisel as it requires one-fifth as much code and is much faster to develop than Verilog.
[src:chisel-hdl/chisel-programming-language] Circuits described in Chisel can be converted to a description in Verilog for synthesis and simulation using a program named FIRRTL.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] In computer engineering, a **hardware description language** (**HDL**) is a specialized computer language used to describe the structure and behavior of electronic circuits, usually to design application-specific integrated circuits (ASICs) and to program field-programmable gate arrays (FPGAs).
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] A hardware description language enables a precise, formal description of an electronic circuit that allows for the automated analysis and simulation of the circuit.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] It also allows for the synthesis of an HDL description into a netlist (a specification of physical electronic components and how they are connected together), which can then be placed and routed to produce the set of masks used to create an integrated circuit.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] A hardware description language looks much like a programming language such as C or ALGOL; it is a textual description consisting of expressions, statements and control structures.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] One important difference between most programming languages and HDLs is that HDLs explicitly include the notion of time.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] HDLs form an integral part of electronic design automation (EDA) systems, especially for complex circuits, such as application-specific integrated circuits, microprocessors, and programmable logic devices.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] HDLs were created to implement register-transfer level abstraction, a model of the dataflow and timing of a circuit.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] Two major hardware description languages exist: VHDL and Verilog.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] In them, three different types of description occur: *dataflow*, *behavioral*, and *structural*.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] HDLs are standard text-based expressions of the structure of electronic systems and their behaviour over time.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] Like concurrent programming languages, HDL syntax and semantics include explicit notations for expressing concurrency.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] However, in contrast to most software programming languages, HDLs also include an explicit notion of time, which is a primary attribute of hardware.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] Languages whose only characteristic is to express circuit connectivity between a hierarchy of blocks are properly classified as netlist languages used in electric computer-aided design.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] HDL can be used to express designs in structural, behavioral or register-transfer-level architectures for the same circuit functionality; in the latter two cases the synthesizer decides the architecture and logic gate layout.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] HDLs are used to write executable specifications for hardware.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] A program designed to implement the underlying semantics of the language statements and simulate the progress of time provides the hardware designer with the ability to model a piece of hardware before it is created physically.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] It is this executability that gives HDLs the illusion of being programming languages, when they are more precisely classified as specification languages or modeling languages.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] Simulators capable of supporting discrete-event (digital) and continuous-time (analog) modeling exist, and HDLs targeted for each are available.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] It is certainly possible to represent hardware semantics using traditional programming languages such as C++, which operate on control flow semantics in contrast to dataflow, although to function as such, programs must be augmented with extensive and unwieldy class libraries.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] Generally, however, software programming languages include no ability to express time explicitly, and thus cannot function as hardware description languages.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] Before the debut of System Verilog in 2002, C++ integration with a logic simulator was one of the few ways to use object-oriented programming in hardware verification.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] System Verilog is the first major HDL to offer object-orientation and garbage collection.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] Using the proper subset of hardware description language, a program called a synthesizer, or logic synthesis tool, can infer hardware logic operations from the language statements and produce an equivalent netlist of generic hardware primitives to implement the specified behaviour.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] Synthesizers generally ignore the expression of any timing constructs in the text.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] Digital logic synthesizers, for example, generally use clock edges as the way to time the circuit, ignoring any timing constructs.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] The ability to have a synthesizable subset of the language does not itself make a hardware description language.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] The first hardware description languages appeared in the late 1960s, looking like more traditional languages.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] The first that had a lasting effect was described in 1971 in C.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] Gordon Bell and Allen Newell's text *Computer Structures*.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] This text introduced the concept of register transfer level, first used in the ISP language to describe the behavior of the Digital Equipment Corporation (DEC) PDP-8.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] The language became more widespread with the introduction of DEC's PDP-16 RT-Level Modules (RTMs) and a book describing their use.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] At least two implementations of the basic ISP language (ISPL and ISPS) followed.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] ISPS was well suited to describe relations between the inputs and the outputs of the design and was quickly adopted by commercial teams at DEC, and by several research teams in the US and among its allies in the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO).
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] The RTM products never succeeded commercially and DEC stopped marketing them in the mid-1980s, as new methods grew more popular, more so very-large-scale integration (VLSI).
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] Separate work done about 1979 at the University of Kaiserslautern produced a language named *KAiserslautern Register Transfer Language* (KARL), which included design calculus language features supporting VLSI chip floorplanning and structured hardware design.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] This work was also the basis of KARL's interactive graphic sister language ABL, whose name was an initialism for "a block diagram language".
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] ABL was implemented in the early 1980s by the Centro Studi e Laboratori Telecomunicazioni (CSELT) in Torino, Italy, producing the ABLED graphic VLSI design editor.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] In the mid-1980s, a VLSI design framework was implemented around KARL and ABL by an international consortium funded by the Commission of the European Union.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] By the late 1970s, design using programmable logic devices (PLDs) became popular, although these designs were primarily limited to designing finite-state machines.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] The work at Data General in 1980 used these same devices to design the Data General Eclipse MV/8000, and commercial need began to grow for a language that could map well to them.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] By 1983 Data I/O introduced ABEL to fill that need.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] In 1985, as design shifted to VLSI, Gateway Design Automation introduced Verilog, and Intermetrics released the first completed version of the VHSIC Hardware Description Language (VHDL).
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] VHDL was developed at the behest of the United States Department of Defense's Very High Speed Integrated Circuit Program (VHSIC), and was based on the Ada programming language, and on the experience gained with the earlier development of ISPS.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] Initially, Verilog and VHDL were used to document and simulate circuit designs already captured and described in another form (such as schematic files).
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] HDL simulation enabled designers to work at a higher level of abstraction than simulation at the schematic level, and thus increased design capacity from hundreds of transistors to thousands.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] In 1986, with the support of the U.S Department of Defense, VHDL was sponsored as an IEEE standard (IEEE Std 1076), and the first IEEE-standardized version of VHDL, IEEE Std 1076-1987, was approved in December 1987.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] Cadence Design Systems later acquired Gateway Design Automation for the rights to Verilog-XL, the HDL simulator that would become the de facto standard of Verilog simulators for the next decade.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] The introduction of logic synthesis for HDLs pushed HDLs from the background into the foreground of digital design.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] Synthesis tools compiled HDL source code files (written in a constrained format named RTL) into a manufacturable netlist description in terms of logic gates and transistors.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] Writing synthesizable RTL files required practice and discipline on the part of the designer; compared to a traditional schematic layout, synthesized RTL netlists were almost always larger in area and slower in performance.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] Within a few years, VHDL and Verilog emerged as the dominant HDLs in the electronics industry, while older and less capable HDLs gradually disappeared from use.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] However, VHDL and Verilog share many of the same limits, such as being unsuitable for analog or mixed-signal circuit simulation.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] Specialized HDLs (such as Confluence) were introduced with the explicit goal of fixing specific limits of Verilog and VHDL, though none were ever intended to replace them.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] Over the years, much effort has been invested in improving HDLs.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] The latest iteration of Verilog, formally named IEEE 1800-2005 SystemVerilog, introduces many new features (classes, random variables, and properties/assertions) to address the growing need for better test bench randomization, design hierarchy, and reuse.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] A future revision of VHDL is also in development, and is expected to match SystemVerilog's improvements.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] As a result of the efficiency gains realized using HDL, a majority of modern digital circuit design revolves around it.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] Most designs begin as a set of requirements or a high-level architectural diagram.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] Control and decision structures are often prototyped in flowchart applications, or entered in a editor.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] The process of writing the HDL description is highly dependent on the nature of the circuit and the designer's preference for coding style.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] The HDL is merely the 'capture language', often beginning with a high-level algorithmic description such as a C++ mathematical model.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] Designers often use scripting languages such as Perl to automatically generate repetitive circuit structures in the HDL language.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] Special text editors offer features for automatic indentation, syntax-dependent coloration, and macro-based expansion of the entity/architecture/signal declaration.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] The HDL code then undergoes a code review, or auditing.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] In preparation for synthesis, the HDL description is subject to an array of automated checkers.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] The checkers report deviations from standardized code guidelines, identify potential ambiguous code constructs before they can cause misinterpretation, and check for common logical coding errors, such as floating ports or shorted outputs.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] This process aids in resolving errors before the code is synthesized.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] In industry parlance, HDL design generally ends at the synthesis stage.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] Once the synthesis tool has mapped the HDL description into a gate netlist, the netlist is passed off to the back-end stage.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] Depending on the physical technology (FPGA, ASIC gate array, ASIC standard cell), HDLs may or may not play a significant role in the back-end flow.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] In general, as the design flow progresses toward a physically realizable form, the design database becomes progressively more laden with technology-specific information, which cannot be stored in a generic HDL description.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] Finally, an integrated circuit is manufactured or programmed for use.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] Essential to HDL design is the ability to simulate HDL programs.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] Simulation allows an HDL description of a design (called a model) to pass design verification, an important milestone that validates the design's intended function (specification) against the code implementation in the HDL description.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] It also permits architectural exploration.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] A designer can experiment with design choices by writing multiple variations of a base design, then comparing their behavior in simulation.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] Thus, simulation is critical for successful HDL design.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] To simulate an HDL model, a designer writes a top-level simulation environment (called a test bench).
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] At minimum, a testbench contains an instantiation of the model (called the device under test or DUT), pin/signal declarations for the model's input/output (I/O), and a clock waveform.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] The testbench code is event driven: a designer writes HDL statements to implement the (testbench-generated) reset-signal, to model interface transactions (such as a host–bus read/write), and to monitor the DUT's output.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] An HDL simulator — the program that executes the testbench — maintains the simulator clock, which is the master reference for all events in the testbench simulation.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] Events occur only at the instants dictated by the testbench HDL (such as a reset-toggle coded into the testbench), or in reaction (by the model) to stimulus and triggering events.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] Modern HDL simulators have full-featured graphical user interfaces, complete with a suite of debug tools.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] These allow the user to stop and restart the simulation at any time, insert simulator breakpoints (independent of the HDL code), and monitor or modify any element in the HDL model hierarchy.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] Modern simulators can also link the HDL environment to user-compiled libraries, through a defined PLI/VHPI interface.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] Linking is system-dependent (x86, SPARC etc. running Windows/Linux/Solaris), as the HDL simulator and user libraries are compiled and linked outside the HDL environment.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] Design verification is often the most time-consuming portion of the design process, due to the disconnect between a device's functional specification, the designer's interpretation of the specification, and the imprecision of the HDL language.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] Most of the initial test/debug cycle is conducted in the HDL *simulator* environment, as the early stage of the design is subject to frequent and major circuit changes.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] An HDL description can also be prototyped and tested in hardware — programmable logic devices are often used for this purpose.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] Hardware prototyping is comparatively more expensive than HDL simulation, but offers a real-world view of the design.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] Prototyping is the best way to check interfacing against other hardware devices and hardware prototypes.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] Even those running on slow FPGAs offer much shorter simulation times than pure HDL simulation.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] Historically, design verification was a laborious, repetitive loop of writing and running simulation test cases against the design under test.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] As chip designs have grown larger and more complex, the task of design verification has grown to the point where it now dominates the schedule of a design team.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] Looking for ways to improve design productivity, the electronic design automation industry developed the Property Specification Language.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] In formal verification terms, a property is a factual statement about the expected or assumed behavior of another object.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] Ideally, for a given HDL description, a property or properties can be proven true or false using formal mathematical methods.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] In practical terms, many properties cannot be proven because they occupy an unbounded solution space.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] However, if provided a set of operating assumptions or constraints, a property checker can prove (or disprove) certain properties by narrowing the solution space.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] The assertions do not model circuit activity, but capture and document the designer's intent in the HDL code.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] In a simulation environment, the simulator evaluates all specified assertions, reporting the location and severity of any violations.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] In a synthesis environment, the synthesis tool usually operates with the policy of halting synthesis upon any violation.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] Assertion based verification is still in its infancy, but is expected to become an integral part of the HDL design toolset.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] An HDL is grossly similar to a software programming language, but there are major differences.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] Most programming languages are inherently procedural (single-threaded), with limited syntactical and semantic support to handle concurrency.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] HDLs, on the other hand, resemble concurrent programming languages in their ability to model multiple parallel processes (such as flip-flops and adders) that automatically execute independently of one another.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] Any change to the process's input automatically triggers an update in the simulator's process stack.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] Both programming languages and HDLs are processed by a compiler (often called a synthesizer in the HDL case), but with different goals.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] For HDLs, "compiling" refers to logic synthesis; the process of transforming the HDL code listing into a physically realizable gate netlist.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] On the other hand, a software compiler converts the source-code listing into a microprocessor-specific object code for execution on the target microprocessor.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] As HDLs and programming languages borrow concepts and features from each other, the boundary between them is becoming less distinct.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] However, pure HDLs are unsuitable for general purpose application software development, just as general-purpose programming languages are undesirable for modeling hardware.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] Yet as electronic systems grow increasingly complex, and reconfigurable systems become increasingly common, there is growing desire in the industry for a single language that can perform some tasks of both hardware design and software programming.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] SystemC is an example of such—embedded system hardware can be modeled as non-detailed architectural blocks (black boxes with modeled signal inputs and output drivers).
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] The target application is written in C or C++ and natively compiled for the host-development system; in contrast to targeting the embedded CPU, which requires host-simulation of the embedded CPU or an emulated CPU.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] The high level of abstraction of SystemC models is well suited to early architecture exploration, as architectural modifications can be easily evaluated with little concern for signal-level implementation issues.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] However, the threading model used in SystemC relies on shared memory, causing the language not to handle parallel execution or low-level models well.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] In their level of abstraction, HDLs have been compared to assembly languages.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] There are attempts to raise the abstraction level of hardware design in order to reduce the complexity of programming in HDLs, creating a sub-field called *high-level synthesis*.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] Companies such as Cadence, Synopsys and Agility Design Solutions are promoting SystemC as a way to combine high-level languages with concurrency models to allow faster design cycles for field-programmable gate arrays (FPGAs) than is possible using traditional HDLs.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] Approaches based on standard C or C++ (with libraries or other extensions allowing parallel programming) are found in the Catapult C tools from Mentor Graphics, and the Impulse C tools from Impulse Accelerated Technologies.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] A similar initiative from Intel is the use of Data Parallel C++, related to SYCL, as a high-level synthesis language.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] It is also possible to design hardware modules using MATLAB and Simulink using the MathWorks HDL Coder tool or DSP Builder for Intel FPGAs or Xilinx System Generator (XSG) from Xilinx.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] The two most widely used and well-supported HDL varieties used in industry are Verilog and VHDL.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] Several projects exist for defining printed circuit board connectivity using language based, textual-entry methods.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] Among these, new approaches have emerged that focus on enhancing readability, reusability, and validation.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] These modern methodologies employ open-source design languages specifically tailored for electronics, adopting declarative markup to specify what circuits should achieve.
[src:chisel-hdl/hardware-description-language] This shift integrates software development principles into hardware design, streamlining the process and emphasizing automation, reuse, and validation.
[src:chisel-hdl/reconfigurable-computing] The concept of reconfigurable computing has existed since the 1960s, when Gerald Estrin's paper proposed the concept of a computer made of a standard processor and an array of "reconfigurable" hardware.
[src:chisel-hdl/reconfigurable-computing] The main processor would control the behavior of the reconfigurable hardware.
[src:chisel-hdl/reconfigurable-computing] The latter would then be tailored to perform a specific task, such as image processing or pattern matching, as quickly as a dedicated piece of hardware.
[src:chisel-hdl/reconfigurable-computing] Once the task was done, the hardware could be adjusted to do some other task.
[src:chisel-hdl/reconfigurable-computing] This resulted in a hybrid computer structure combining the flexibility of software with the speed of hardware.
[src:chisel-hdl/reconfigurable-computing] In the 1980s and 1990s there was a renaissance in this area of research with many proposed reconfigurable architectures developed in industry and academia, such as: Copacobana, Matrix, GARP, Elixent, NGEN, Polyp, MereGen, PACT XPP, Silicon Hive, Montium, Pleiades, Morphosys, and PiCoGA.
[src:chisel-hdl/reconfigurable-computing] Such designs were feasible due to the constant progress of silicon technology that let complex designs be implemented on one chip.
[src:chisel-hdl/reconfigurable-computing] Some of these massively parallel reconfigurable computers were built primarily for special subdomains such as molecular evolution, neural or image processing.
[src:chisel-hdl/reconfigurable-computing] The world's first commercial reconfigurable computer, the Algotronix CHS2X4, was completed in 1991.
[src:chisel-hdl/reconfigurable-computing] It was not a commercial success, but was promising enough that Xilinx (the inventor of the field-programmable gate array, FPGA) bought the technology and hired the Algotronix staff.
[src:chisel-hdl/reconfigurable-computing] Later machines enabled first demonstrations of scientific principles, such as the spontaneous spatial self-organisation of genetic coding with MereGen.
[src:chisel-hdl/reconfigurable-computing] Computer scientist Reiner Hartenstein describes reconfigurable computing in terms of an *anti-machine* that, according to him, represents a fundamental paradigm shift away from the more conventional von Neumann machine.
[src:chisel-hdl/reconfigurable-computing] This paradox is partly explained by the von Neumann syndrome.
[src:chisel-hdl/reconfigurable-computing] The increase of logic in an FPGA has enabled larger and more complex algorithms to be programmed into the FPGA.
[src:chisel-hdl/reconfigurable-computing] The attachment of such an FPGA to a modern CPU over a high speed bus, like PCI express, has enabled the configurable logic to act more like a coprocessor rather than a peripheral.
[src:chisel-hdl/reconfigurable-computing] This has brought reconfigurable computing into the high-performance computing sphere.
[src:chisel-hdl/reconfigurable-computing] Furthermore, by replicating an algorithm on an FPGA or the use of a multiplicity of FPGAs has enabled reconfigurable SIMD systems to be produced where several computational devices can concurrently operate on different data, which is highly parallel computing.
[src:chisel-hdl/reconfigurable-computing] This heterogeneous systems technique is used in computing research and especially in supercomputing.
[src:chisel-hdl/reconfigurable-computing] A 2008 paper reported speed-up factors of more than 4 orders of magnitude and energy saving factors by up to almost 4 orders of magnitude.
[src:chisel-hdl/reconfigurable-computing] Some supercomputer firms offer heterogeneous processing blocks including FPGAs as accelerators.
[src:chisel-hdl/reconfigurable-computing] One research area is the twin-paradigm programming tool flow productivity obtained for such heterogeneous systems.
[src:chisel-hdl/reconfigurable-computing] The US National Science Foundation has a center for high-performance reconfigurable computing (CHREC).
[src:chisel-hdl/reconfigurable-computing] In April 2011 the fourth Many-core and Reconfigurable Supercomputing Conference was held in Europe.
[src:chisel-hdl/reconfigurable-computing] Commercial high-performance reconfigurable computing systems are beginning to emerge with the announcement of IBM integrating FPGAs with its IBM Power microprocessors.
[src:chisel-hdl/reconfigurable-computing] Electronic hardware, like software, can be designed modularly, by creating subcomponents and then higher-level components to instantiate them.
[src:chisel-hdl/reconfigurable-computing] In many cases it is useful to be able to swap out one or several of these subcomponents while the FPGA is still operating.
[src:chisel-hdl/reconfigurable-computing] Normally, reconfiguring an FPGA requires it to be held in reset while an external controller reloads a design onto it.
[src:chisel-hdl/reconfigurable-computing] Partial reconfiguration allows for critical parts of the design to continue operating while a controller either on the FPGA or off of it loads a partial design into a reconfigurable module.
[src:chisel-hdl/reconfigurable-computing] Partial reconfiguration also can be used to save space for multiple designs by only storing the partial designs that change between designs.
[src:chisel-hdl/reconfigurable-computing] A common example for when partial reconfiguration would be useful is the case of a communication device.
[src:chisel-hdl/reconfigurable-computing] If the device is controlling multiple connections, some of which require encryption, it would be useful to be able to load different encryption cores without bringing the whole controller down.
[src:chisel-hdl/reconfigurable-computing] Partial reconfiguration is not supported on all FPGAs.
[src:chisel-hdl/reconfigurable-computing] A special software flow with emphasis on modular design is required.
[src:chisel-hdl/reconfigurable-computing] Typically the design modules are built along well defined boundaries inside the FPGA that require the design to be specially mapped to the internal hardware.
[src:chisel-hdl/reconfigurable-computing] With the advent of affordable FPGA boards, students' and hobbyists' projects seek to recreate vintage computers or implement more novel architectures.
[src:chisel-hdl/reconfigurable-computing] Such projects are built with reconfigurable hardware (FPGAs), and some devices support emulation of multiple vintage computers using a single reconfigurable hardware (C-One).
[src:chisel-hdl/reconfigurable-computing] A fully FPGA-based computer is the COPACOBANA, the *cost-optimized codebreaker and analyzer* and its successor RIVYERA.
[src:chisel-hdl/reconfigurable-computing] A spin-off company SciEngines GmbH of the COPACOBANA-Project of the Universities of Bochum and Kiel in Germany continues the development of fully FPGA-based computers.
[src:chisel-hdl/reconfigurable-computing] Mitrionics has developed a SDK that enables software written using a single assignment language to be compiled and executed on FPGA-based computers.
[src:chisel-hdl/reconfigurable-computing] National Instruments have developed a hybrid embedded computing system called CompactRIO.
[src:chisel-hdl/reconfigurable-computing] It consists of reconfigurable chassis housing the user-programmable FPGA, hot swappable I/O modules, real-time controller for deterministic communication and processing, and graphical LabVIEW software for rapid RT and FPGA programming.
[src:chisel-hdl/reconfigurable-computing] Xilinx has developed two styles of partial reconfiguration of FPGA devices: *module-based* and *difference-based*.
[src:chisel-hdl/reconfigurable-computing] *Module-based partial reconfiguration* permits to reconfigure distinct modular parts of the design, while *difference-based partial reconfiguration* can be used when a small change is made to a design.
[src:chisel-hdl/reconfigurable-computing] Intel supports partial reconfiguration of their FPGA devices on 28 nm devices such as Stratix V, and on the 20 nm Arria 10 devices.
[src:chisel-hdl/reconfigurable-computing] The Intel FPGA partial reconfiguration flow for Arria 10 is based on the hierarchical design methodology in the Quartus Prime Pro software where users create physical partitions of the FPGA that can be reconfigured at runtime while the remainder of the design continues to operate.
[src:chisel-hdl/reconfigurable-computing] The Quartus Prime Pro software also support hierarchical partial reconfiguration and simulation of partial reconfiguration.
[src:chisel-hdl/reconfigurable-computing] As an emerging field, classifications of reconfigurable architectures are still being developed and refined as new architectures are developed; no unifying taxonomy has been suggested to date.
[src:chisel-hdl/reconfigurable-computing] However, several recurring parameters can be used to classify these systems.
[src:chisel-hdl/reconfigurable-computing] The granularity of the reconfigurable logic is defined as the size of the smallest functional unit (configurable logic block, CLB) that is addressed by the mapping tools.
[src:chisel-hdl/reconfigurable-computing] High granularity, which can also be known as fine-grained, often implies a greater flexibility when implementing algorithms into the hardware.
[src:chisel-hdl/reconfigurable-computing] However, there is a penalty associated with this in terms of increased power, area and delay due to greater quantity of routing required per computation.
[src:chisel-hdl/reconfigurable-computing] Fine-grained architectures work at the bit-level manipulation level; whilst coarse grained processing elements (reconfigurable datapath unit, rDPU) are better optimised for standard data path applications.
[src:chisel-hdl/reconfigurable-computing] One of the drawbacks of coarse grained architectures are that they tend to lose some of their utilisation and performance if they need to perform smaller computations than their granularity provides, for example for a one bit add on a four bit wide functional unit would waste three bits.
[src:chisel-hdl/reconfigurable-computing] This problem can be solved by having a coarse grain array (reconfigurable datapath array, rDPA) and a FPGA on the same chip.
[src:chisel-hdl/reconfigurable-computing] Coarse-grained architectures (rDPA) are intended for the implementation for algorithms needing word-width data paths (rDPU).
[src:chisel-hdl/reconfigurable-computing] A potential undesirable consequence of having larger computational blocks is that when the size of operands may not match the algorithm an inefficient utilisation of resources can result.
[src:chisel-hdl/reconfigurable-computing] Often the type of applications to be run are known in advance allowing the logic, memory and routing resources to be tailored to enhance the performance of the device whilst still providing a certain level of flexibility for future adaptation.
[src:chisel-hdl/reconfigurable-computing] Examples of this are domain specific arrays aimed at gaining better performance in terms of power, area, throughput than their more generic finer grained FPGA cousins by reducing their flexibility.
[src:chisel-hdl/reconfigurable-computing] Configuration of these reconfigurable systems can happen at deployment time, between execution phases or during execution.
[src:chisel-hdl/reconfigurable-computing] In a typical reconfigurable system, a bit stream is used to program the device at deployment time.
[src:chisel-hdl/reconfigurable-computing] Fine grained systems by their own nature require greater configuration time than more coarse-grained architectures due to more elements needing to be addressed and programmed.
[src:chisel-hdl/reconfigurable-computing] Therefore, more coarse-grained architectures gain from potential lower energy requirements, as less information is transferred and utilised.
[src:chisel-hdl/reconfigurable-computing] Intuitively, the slower the rate of reconfiguration the smaller the power consumption as the associated energy cost of reconfiguration are amortised over a longer period of time.
[src:chisel-hdl/reconfigurable-computing] Partial re-configuration aims to allow part of the device to be reprogrammed while another part is still performing active computation.
[src:chisel-hdl/reconfigurable-computing] Partial re-configuration allows smaller reconfigurable bit streams thus not wasting energy on transmitting redundant information in the bit stream.
[src:chisel-hdl/reconfigurable-computing] Compression of the bit stream is possible but careful analysis is to be carried out to ensure that the energy saved by using smaller bit streams is not outweighed by the computation needed to decompress the data.
[src:chisel-hdl/reconfigurable-computing] Often the reconfigurable array is used as a processing accelerator attached to a host processor.
[src:chisel-hdl/reconfigurable-computing] The level of coupling determines the type of data transfers, latency, power, throughput and overheads involved when utilising the reconfigurable logic.
[src:chisel-hdl/reconfigurable-computing] Some of the most intuitive designs use a peripheral bus to provide a coprocessor like arrangement for the reconfigurable array.
[src:chisel-hdl/reconfigurable-computing] However, there have also been implementations where the reconfigurable fabric is much closer to the processor, some are even implemented into the data path, utilising the processor registers.
[src:chisel-hdl/reconfigurable-computing] The job of the host processor is to perform the control functions, configure the logic, schedule data and to provide external interfacing.
[src:chisel-hdl/reconfigurable-computing] The flexibility in reconfigurable devices mainly comes from their routing interconnect.
[src:chisel-hdl/reconfigurable-computing] One style of interconnect made popular by FPGAs vendors, Xilinx and Altera are the island style layout, where blocks are arranged in an array with vertical and horizontal routing.
[src:chisel-hdl/reconfigurable-computing] A layout with inadequate routing may suffer from poor flexibility and resource utilisation, therefore providing limited performance.
[src:chisel-hdl/reconfigurable-computing] If too much interconnect is provided this requires more transistors than necessary and thus more silicon area, longer wires and more power consumption.
[src:chisel-hdl/reconfigurable-computing] One of the key challenges for reconfigurable computing is to enable higher design productivity and provide an easier way to use reconfigurable computing systems for users that are unfamiliar with the underlying concepts.
[src:chisel-hdl/reconfigurable-computing] One way of doing this is to provide standardization and abstraction, usually supported and enforced by an operating system.
[src:chisel-hdl/reconfigurable-computing] One of the major tasks of an operating system is to hide the hardware and present programs (and their programmers) with nice, clean, elegant, and consistent abstractions to work with instead.
[src:chisel-hdl/reconfigurable-computing] In other words, the two main tasks of an operating system are abstraction and resource management.
[src:chisel-hdl/reconfigurable-computing] Abstraction is a powerful mechanism to handle complex and different (hardware) tasks in a well-defined and common manner.
[src:chisel-hdl/reconfigurable-computing] One of the most elementary OS abstractions is a process.
[src:chisel-hdl/reconfigurable-computing] A process is a running application that has the perception (provided by the OS) that it is running on its own on the underlying virtual hardware.
[src:chisel-hdl/reconfigurable-computing] This can be relaxed by the concept of threads, allowing different tasks to run concurrently on this virtual hardware to exploit task level parallelism.
[src:chisel-hdl/reconfigurable-computing] To allow different processes and threads to coordinate their work, communication and synchronization methods have to be provided by the OS.
[src:chisel-hdl/reconfigurable-computing] In addition to abstraction, resource management of the underlying hardware components is necessary because the virtual computers provided to the processes and threads by the operating system need to share available physical resources (processors, memory, and devices) spatially and temporarily.
[src:chisel-hdl/register-transfer-level] In digital circuit design, **register-transfer level** (**RTL**) is a design abstraction which models a synchronous digital circuit in terms of the flow of digital signals (data) between hardware registers, and the logical operations performed on those signals.
[src:chisel-hdl/register-transfer-level] Register-transfer-level abstraction is used in hardware description languages (HDLs) like Verilog and VHDL to create high-level representations of a circuit, from which lower-level representations and ultimately actual wiring can be derived.
[src:chisel-hdl/register-transfer-level] Design at the RTL level is typical practice in modern digital design.
[src:chisel-hdl/register-transfer-level] Unlike in software compiler design, where the register-transfer level is an intermediate representation and at the lowest level, the RTL level is the usual input that circuit designers operate on.
[src:chisel-hdl/register-transfer-level] In circuit synthesis, an intermediate language between the input register transfer level representation and the target netlist is sometimes used.
[src:chisel-hdl/register-transfer-level] Unlike in netlist, constructs such as cells, functions, and multi-bit registers are available.
[src:chisel-hdl/register-transfer-level] Transaction-level modeling is a higher level of electronic system design.
[src:chisel-hdl/register-transfer-level] A synchronous circuit consists of two kinds of elements: registers (sequential logic) and combinational logic.
[src:chisel-hdl/register-transfer-level] Registers (usually implemented as D flip-flops) synchronize the circuit's operation to the edges of the clock signal, and are the only elements in the circuit that have memory properties.
[src:chisel-hdl/register-transfer-level] Combinational logic performs all the logical functions in the circuit and it typically consists of logic gates.
[src:chisel-hdl/register-transfer-level] For example, a very simple synchronous circuit is shown in the figure.
[src:chisel-hdl/register-transfer-level] The inverter is connected from the output, Q, of a register to the register's input, D, to create a circuit that changes its state on each rising edge of the clock, clk.
[src:chisel-hdl/register-transfer-level] In this circuit, the combinational logic consists of the inverter.
[src:chisel-hdl/register-transfer-level] When designing digital integrated circuits with a hardware description language (HDL), the designs are usually engineered at a higher level of abstraction than transistor level (logic families) or logic gate level.
[src:chisel-hdl/register-transfer-level] In HDLs the designer declares the registers (which roughly correspond to variables in computer programming languages), and describes the combinational logic by using constructs that are familiar from programming languages such as if-then-else and arithmetic operations.
[src:chisel-hdl/register-transfer-level] This level is called *register-transfer level*.
[src:chisel-hdl/register-transfer-level] The term refers to the fact that RTL focuses on describing the flow of signals between registers.
[src:chisel-hdl/register-transfer-level] Using an EDA tool for synthesis, this description can usually be directly translated to an equivalent hardware implementation file for an ASIC or an FPGA.
[src:chisel-hdl/register-transfer-level] The synthesis tool also performs logic optimization.
[src:chisel-hdl/register-transfer-level] At the register-transfer level, some types of circuits can be recognized.
[src:chisel-hdl/register-transfer-level] If there is a cyclic path of logic from a register's output to its input (or from a set of registers outputs to its inputs), the circuit is called a state machine or can be said to be sequential logic.
[src:chisel-hdl/register-transfer-level] If there are logic paths from a register to another without a cycle, it is called a pipeline.
[src:chisel-hdl/register-transfer-level] RTL is used in the logic design phase of the integrated circuit design cycle.
[src:chisel-hdl/register-transfer-level] An RTL description is usually converted to a gate-level description of the circuit by a logic synthesis tool.
[src:chisel-hdl/register-transfer-level] The synthesis results are then used by placement and routing tools to create a physical layout.
[src:chisel-hdl/register-transfer-level] Logic simulation tools may use a design's RTL description to verify its correctness.
[src:chisel-hdl/register-transfer-level] The most accurate power analysis tools are available for the circuit level but unfortunately, even with switch- rather than device-level modelling, tools at the circuit level have disadvantages like they are either too slow or require too much memory thus inhibiting large chip handling.
[src:chisel-hdl/register-transfer-level] The majority of these are simulators like SPICE and have been used by the designers for many years as performance analysis tools.
[src:chisel-hdl/register-transfer-level] Due to these disadvantages, gate-level power estimation tools have begun to gain some acceptance where faster, probabilistic techniques have begun to gain a foothold.
[src:chisel-hdl/register-transfer-level] But it also has its trade off as speedup is achieved on the cost of accuracy, especially in the presence of correlated signals.
[src:chisel-hdl/register-transfer-level] Over the years it has been realized that biggest wins in low power design cannot come from circuit- and gate-level optimizations whereas architecture, system, and algorithm optimizations tend to have the largest impact on power consumption.
[src:chisel-hdl/register-transfer-level] Therefore, there has been a shift in the incline of the tool developers towards high-level analysis and optimization tools for power.
[src:chisel-hdl/register-transfer-level] This in no way implies that lower level tools are unimportant.
[src:chisel-hdl/register-transfer-level] Instead, each layer of tools provides a foundation upon which the next level can be built.
[src:chisel-hdl/register-transfer-level] The abstractions of the estimation techniques at a lower level can be used on a higher level with slight modifications.
[src:chisel-hdl/register-transfer-level] It is a technique based on the concept of gate equivalents.
[src:chisel-hdl/register-transfer-level] The complexity of a chip architecture can be described approximately in terms of gate equivalents where gate equivalent count specifies the average number of reference gates that are required to implement the particular function.
[src:chisel-hdl/register-transfer-level] The total power required for the particular function is estimated by multiplying the approximated number of gate equivalents with the average power consumed per gate.
[src:chisel-hdl/register-transfer-level] Assign a complexity in terms of gate equivalents.
[src:chisel-hdl/register-transfer-level] The number of GE’s for each unit type are either taken directly as an input from the user or are fed from a library.
[src:chisel-hdl/register-transfer-level] is the assumed average dissipated energy by a gate equivalent, when active.
[src:chisel-hdl/register-transfer-level] , denotes the average percentage of gates switching per clock cycle and is allowed to vary from function to function.
[src:chisel-hdl/register-transfer-level] , is a combination of fan-out loading as well as wiring.
[src:chisel-hdl/register-transfer-level] An estimate of the average wire length can be used to calculate the wiring capacitance.
[src:chisel-hdl/register-transfer-level] The percentage of gates switching per clock cycle denoted by activity factors are assumed to be fixed regardless of the input patterns.
[src:chisel-hdl/register-transfer-level] Typical gate switching energy is characterized by completely random uniform white noise (UWN) distribution of the input data.
[src:chisel-hdl/register-transfer-level] This implies that the power estimation is same regardless of the circuit being idle or at maximum load as this UWN model ignores how different input distributions affect the power consumption of gates and modules.
[src:chisel-hdl/register-transfer-level] denotes the loading due to a single cell hanging off the bit line.
[src:chisel-hdl/register-transfer-level] The chosen activity factor gives the correct total power, but the breakdown of power into logic, clock, memory, etc. is less accurate.
[src:chisel-hdl/register-transfer-level] Therefore this tool is not much different or improved in comparison with CES.
[src:chisel-hdl/register-transfer-level] Where Ki is PFA proportionality constant that characterizes the ith functional element $G_{i}$ is the measure of hardware complexity, and $f_{i}$ denotes the activation frequency.
[src:chisel-hdl/register-transfer-level] Gi denoting the hardware complexity of the multiplier is related to the square of the input word length i.e.
[src:chisel-hdl/register-transfer-level] The activation frequency is the rate at which multiplies are performed by the algorithm denoted by $f_{mult}$ and the PFA constant, $K_{mult}$ , is extracted empirically from past multiplier designs and shown to be about 15 fW/bit2-Hz for a 1.2 μm technology at 5V.
[src:chisel-hdl/register-transfer-level] The estimation error (relative to switch-level simulation) for a 16x16 multiplier is experimented and it is observed that when the dynamic range of the inputs does not fully occupy the word length of the multiplier, the UWN model becomes extremely inaccurate.
[src:chisel-hdl/register-transfer-level] Granted, good designers attempt to maximize word length utilization.
[src:chisel-hdl/register-transfer-level] Still, errors in the range of 50-100% are not uncommon.
[src:chisel-hdl/register-transfer-level] The figure clearly suggests a flaw in the UWN model.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p01] RISC-V was developed in 2010 at the University of California, Berkeley as the fifth generation of RISC processors created at the university since 1981.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p01] In 2015, development and maintenance of the standard was transferred to **RISC-V International**, a non-profit organization based in Switzerland with more than 4,500 members as of 2025.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p01] RISC-V is a popular architecture for microcontrollers and embedded systems, with development of higher-performance implementations targeting mobile, desktop, and server markets ongoing.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p01] Before then, there was some knowledge (see John Cocke) that simpler computers can be effective, but the design principles were not widely described.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p01] Simple, effective computers have always been of academic interest, and resulted in the RISC instruction set DLX for the first edition of *Computer Architecture: A Quantitative Approach* in 1990 of which David Patterson was a co-author, and he later participated in the RISC-V origination.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p01] DLX was intended for educational use; academics and hobbyists implemented it using field-programmable gate arrays (FPGA), but it was never truly intended for commercial deployment.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p01] Krste Asanović at the University of California, Berkeley, had a research requirement for an open-source CPU core, and in 2010, he decided to develop and publish his own, in a "short, three-month project over the summer" with several of his graduate students.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p01] Several established open-source alternatives were available, but Asanović chose not to use them.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p01] ARM and SuperH CPUs (versions 2 and earlier) had public-domain instruction sets with VHDL implementation files, while complete OpenRISC, OpenPOWER, and OpenSPARC / LEON cores were also available either as VHDL files or from various vendors.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p01] All of these existing options were supported by the GNU Compiler Collection (GCC), a popular free-software compiler, and had Linux kernel support.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p01] The plan was to aid both academic and industrial users.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p01] At this stage, students provided initial software, simulations, and CPU designs.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p01] The RISC-V authors and their institution originally sourced the ISA documents and several CPU designs under BSD licenses, which allow derivative works—such as RISC-V chip designs—to be either open and free, or closed and proprietary.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p01] The ISA specification itself (i.e., the encoding of the instruction set) was published in 2011 as open source, with all rights reserved.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p01] The actual technical report (an expression of the specification) was later placed under the license Creative Commons - Attribution 4.0 to permit enhancement by external contributors through the RISC-V Foundation, and later RISC-V International.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p01] A full history of RISC-V has been published on the RISC-V International website.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p01] Commercial users require an ISA to be stable before they can use it in a product that may last many years.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p01] To address this issue, the RISC-V Foundation was formed in 2015 to own, maintain, and publish intellectual property related to RISC-V's definition.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p01] The original authors and owners have surrendered their rights to the foundation.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p01] The foundation was led by CEO Calista Redmond, who took on the role in 2019 after leading open infrastructure projects at IBM.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p01] In November 2019, the RISC-V Foundation announced that it would relocate to Switzerland, citing concerns over U.S. trade regulations.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p01] As of March 2020, the organization was named RISC-V International, a Swiss nonprofit business association.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p01] As of 2019, RISC-V International freely publishes the documents defining RISC-V and permits unrestricted use of the ISA for design of software and hardware.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p01] However, only members of RISC-V International can vote to approve changes, and only member organizations use the trademarked compatibility logo.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p01] The Linux Foundation Europe started the RISC-V Software Ecosystem (RISE) initiative on May 31, 2023.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p01] The goal of RISE is to increase the availability of software for high-performance and power-efficient RISC-V processors running high-level operating systems for a range of market segments by bringing together a large number of hardware and software vendors.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p01] Red Hat, Samsung, Qualcomm, Nvidia, MediaTek, Intel, and Google are among the initial members.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p01] CPU design requires design expertise in several specialties: electronic digital logic, compilers, and operating systems.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p01] To cover the costs of such a team, commercial vendors of processor intellectual property (IP), such as Arm Ltd. and MIPS Technologies, charge royalties for the use of their designs and patents.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p01] They also often require non-disclosure agreements before releasing documents that describe their designs' detailed advantages.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p01] In many cases, they never describe the reasons for their design choices.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p01] RISC-V was begun with a goal to make a practical ISA that was open-sourced, usable academically, and deployable in any hardware or software design without royalties.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p01] Also, justifying rationales for each design decision of the project are explained, at least in broad terms.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p01] The RISC-V authors are academics who have substantial experience in computer design, and the RISC-V ISA is a direct development from a series of academic computer-design projects, especially Berkeley RISC.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p01] RISC-V was originated in part to aid all such projects.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p01] To build a large, continuing community of users and thereby accumulate designs and software, the RISC-V ISA designers intentionally support a wide variety of practical use cases: compact, performance, and low-power real-world implementations without over-architecting for a given microarchitecture.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p01] The requirements of a large base of contributors is part of the reason why RISC-V was engineered to address many possible uses.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p01] The designers' primary assertion is that the instruction set is the key interface in a computer as it is situated at the interface between the hardware and the software.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p01] If a good instruction set were open and available for use by all, then it can dramatically reduce the cost of software by enabling far more reuse.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p01] It should also trigger increased competition among hardware providers, who can then devote more resources toward design and less for software support.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p01] The designers maintain that new principles are becoming rare in instruction set design, as the most successful designs of the last forty years have grown increasingly similar.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p01] Of those that failed, most did so because their sponsoring companies were financially unsuccessful, not because the instruction sets were technically poor.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p01] Thus, a well-designed open instruction set designed using well-established principles should attract long-term support by many vendors.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p01] The simplicity of the integer subset permits basic student exercises, and is a simple enough ISA to enable software to control research machines.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p01] The variable-length ISA provides room for instruction set extensions for both student exercises and research, and the separated privileged instruction set permits research in operating system support without redesigning compilers.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p01] RISC-V's open intellectual property paradigm allows derivative designs to be published, reused, and modified.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p01] RISC-V has a modular design, consisting of alternative base parts, with added optional extensions.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p01] The ISA base and its extensions are developed in a collective effort between industry, the research community and educational institutions.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p01] The base specifies instructions (and their encoding), control flow, registers (and their sizes), memory and addressing, logic (i.e., integer) manipulation, and ancillaries.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p01] The base alone can implement a simplified general-purpose computer, with full software support, including a general-purpose compiler.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p01] The standard extensions are specified to work with all of the standard bases, and with each other without conflict.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p01] Many RISC-V computers might implement the compressed instructions extension, C, to reduce power consumption, code size, and memory use.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p01] There are also future plans to support hypervisors and virtualization.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p01] To name the combinations of functions that may be implemented, a nomenclature is defined to specify them in Chapter 27 of the current ratified Unprivileged ISA Specification.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p01] The instruction set base is specified first, coding for RISC-V, the register bit-width, and the variant; e.g., RV64I or RV32E.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p01] Then follows letters specifying implemented extensions, in the order of the above table.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p01] Each letter may be followed by a major optionally followed by "p" and a minor option number.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p01] It defaults to 0 if a minor version number is absent, and 1.0 if all of a version number is absent.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p01] Thus RV64IMAFD may be written as RV64I1p0M1p0A1p0F1p0D1p0 or more simply as RV64I1M1A1F1D1.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p01] Underscores may be used between extensions for readability, for example RV32I2_M2_A2.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p01] The base, extended integer & floating-point calculations, with synchronization primitives for multi-core computing, are considered to be necessary for general-purpose computing, and thus we have the shorthand, "G".
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p01] A small 32-bit computer for an embedded system might be RV32EC.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p01] A large 64-bit computer might be RV64GC; i.e., RV64IMAFDCZicsr_Zifencei.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p01] With the growth in the number of extensions, the standard now provides for extensions to be named by a single "Z" followed by an alphabetical name and an optional version number.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p01] For example, Zifencei names the instruction-fetch extension.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p01] Zifencei2 and Zifencei2p0 name version 2.0 of the same.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p01] The first letter following the "Z" by convention indicates the most closely related alphabetical extension category, IMAFDQLCBJTPVN.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p01] Thus the Zam extension for misaligned atomics relates to the "A" standard extension.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p01] Unlike single character extensions, Z extensions must be separated by underscores, grouped by category and then alphabetically within each category.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p01] Extensions specific to supervisor privilege level are named in the same way using "S" for prefix.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p01] Extensions specific to hypervisor level are named using "H" for prefix.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p01] Machine level extensions are prefixed with the three letters "Zxm".
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p01] Supervisor, hypervisor and machine level instruction set extensions are named after less privileged extensions.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p01] RISC-V developers may create their own non-standard instruction set extensions.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p01] These follow the "Z" naming convention, but with "X" as the prefix.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p01] They should be specified after all standard extensions, and if multiple non-standard extensions are listed, they should be listed alphabetically.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p01] Profiles and platforms for standard ISA choice lists are under discussion.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] As a RISC architecture, the RISC-V ISA is a load–store architecture.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] Its floating-point instructions use IEEE 754 floating-point.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] Notable features of the RISC-V ISA include: instruction bit field locations chosen to simplify the use of multiplexers in a CPU, a design that is architecturally neutral, and a fixed location for the sign bit of immediate values to speed up sign extension.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] The instruction set is designed for a wide range of uses.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] The base instruction set has a fixed length of 32-bit naturally aligned instructions, and the ISA supports variable length extensions where each instruction can be any number of 16-bit parcels in length.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] Extensions support small embedded systems, personal computers, supercomputers with vector processors, and warehouse-scale parallel computers.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] The instruction set specification defines 32-bit and 64-bit address space variants.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] The specification includes a description of a 128-bit flat address space variant, as an extrapolation of 32- and 64-bit variants, but the 128-bit ISA remains "not frozen" intentionally, because as of 2023, there is still little practical experience with such large memory systems.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] Unlike other academic designs which are typically optimized only for simplicity of exposition, the designers intended that the RISC-V instruction set be usable for practical computers.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] As of June 2019, version 2.2 of the user-space ISA and version 1.11 of the privileged ISA are frozen, permitting software and hardware development to proceed.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] The user-space ISA, now renamed the Unprivileged ISA, was updated, ratified and frozen as version 20191213.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] An external debug specification is available as a draft, version 0.13.2.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] RISC-V has 32 integer registers (or 16 in the embedded variant), and when the floating-point extension is implemented, an additional 32 floating-point registers.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] Except for memory access instructions, instructions address only registers.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] The first integer register is a zero register, and the remainder are general-purpose registers.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] A store to the zero register has no effect, and a read always provides 0.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] Using the zero register as a placeholder makes for a simpler instruction set.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] Control and status registers exist, but user-mode programs can access only those used for performance measurement and floating-point management.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] No instructions exist to save and restore multiple registers.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] Those were thought to be needless, too complex, and perhaps too slow.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] Like many RISC designs, RISC-V is a load–store architecture: instructions address only registers, with load and store instructions conveying data to and from memory.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] Most load and store instructions include a 12-bit offset and two register identifiers.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] The other register is the destination (for a load) or the source (for a store).
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] The offset is added to a base register to get the address.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] Forming the address as a base register plus offset allows single instructions to access data structures.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] For example, if the base register points to the top of a stack, single instructions can access a subroutine's local variables in the stack.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] Likewise the load and store instructions can access a record-style structure or a memory-mapped I/O device.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] Using the constant zero register as a base address allows single instructions to access memory near address zero.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] Memory is addressed as 8-bit bytes, with instructions being in little-endian order, and with data being in the byte order defined by the execution environment interface in which code is running.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] Words, up to the register size, can be accessed with the load and store instructions.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] RISC-V was originally specified as little-endian to resemble other familiar, successful computers, for example, x86.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] This also reduces a CPU's complexity and costs slightly less because it reads all sizes of words in the same order.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] For example, the RISC-V instruction set decodes starting at the lowest-addressed byte of the instruction.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] Big-endian and bi-endian variants were defined for support of legacy code bases that assume big-endianness.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] An execution environment interface may allow accessed memory addresses not to be aligned to their word width, but accesses to aligned addresses may be faster; for example, simple CPUs may implement unaligned accesses with slow software emulation driven from an alignment failure interrupt.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] Like many RISC instruction sets (and some complex instruction set computer (CISC) instruction sets, such as x86 and IBM System/360 and its successors through z/Architecture), RISC-V lacks address-modes that write back to the registers.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] For example, it does not auto-increment.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] RISC-V manages memory systems that are shared between CPUs or threads by ensuring a thread of execution always sees its memory operations in the programmed order.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] But between threads and I/O devices, RISC-V is simplified: it doesn't guarantee the order of memory operations, except by specific instructions, such as `fence`.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] A `fence` instruction guarantees that the results of predecessor operations are visible to successor operations of other threads or I/O devices.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] `fence` can guarantee the order of combinations of both memory and memory-mapped I/O operations.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] E.g. it can separate memory read and write operations, without affecting I/O operations.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] Or, if a system can operate I/O devices in parallel with memory, `fence` doesn't force them to wait for each other.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] One CPU with one thread may decode `fence` as `nop`.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] Some RISC CPUs (such as MIPS, PowerPC, DLX, and Berkeley's RISC-I) place 16 bits of offset in the loads and stores.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] They set the upper 16 bits by a *load upper word* instruction.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] This permits upper-halfword values to be set easily, without shifting bits.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] However, most use of the upper half-word instruction makes 32-bit constants, like addresses.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] RISC-V uses a SPARC-like combination of 12-bit offsets and 20-bit *set upper* instructions.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] The smaller 12-bit offset helps compact, 32-bit load and store instructions select two of 32 registers yet still have enough bits to support RISC-V's variable-length instruction coding.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] RISC-V handles 32-bit constants and addresses with instructions that set the upper 20 bits of a 32-bit register.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] Load upper immediate `lui` loads 20 bits into bits 31 through 12.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] Then a second instruction such as `addi` can set the bottom 12 bits.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] Small numbers or addresses can be formed by using the zero register instead of `lui`.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] This method is extended to permit position-independent code by adding an instruction, `auipc` that generates 20 upper address bits by adding an offset to the program counter and storing the result into a base register.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] This permits a program to generate 32-bit addresses that are relative to the program counter.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] The base register can often be used as-is with the 12-bit offsets of the loads and stores.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] If needed, `addi` can set the lower 12 bits of a register.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] In 64-bit and 128-bit ISAs,`lui` and `auipc` sign-extend the result to get the larger address.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] Some fast CPUs may interpret combinations of instructions as single *fused* instructions.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] `lui` or `auipc` are good candidates to fuse with `jalr`, `addi`, loads or stores.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] RISC-V's subroutine call `jal` (jump and link) places its return address in a register.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] This is faster in many computer designs, because it saves a memory access compared to systems that push a return address directly on a stack in memory.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] `jal` has a 20-bit signed (two's complement) offset.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] The offset is multiplied by 2, then added to the PC (program counter) to generate a relative address to a 32-bit instruction.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] If the resulting address is not 32-bit aligned (i.e. evenly divisible by 4), the CPU may force an exception.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] RISC-V CPUs jump to calculated addresses using a *jump and link-register*, `jalr` instruction.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] `jalr` is similar to `jal`, but gets its destination address by adding a 12-bit offset to a base register.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] `jalr`'s bit format is like the register-relative loads and stores.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] Like them, `jalr` can be used with the instructions that set the upper 20 bits of a base register to make 32-bit branches, either to an absolute address (using `lui`) or a PC-relative one (using `auipc` for position-independent code).
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] RISC-V recycles `jal` and `jalr` to get unconditional 20-bit PC-relative jumps and unconditional register-based 12-bit jumps.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] Jumps just make the linkage register 0 so that no return address is saved.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] RISC-V also recycles `jalr` to return from a subroutine: To do this, `jalr`'s base register is set to be the linkage register saved by `jal` or `jalr`.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] `jalr`'s offset is zero and the linkage register is zero, so that there is no offset, and no return address is saved.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] Like many RISC designs, in a subroutine call, a RISC-V compiler must use individual instructions to save registers to the stack at the start, and then restore these from the stack on exit.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] RISC-V has no *save multiple* or *restore multiple* register instructions.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] These were thought to make the CPU too complex, and possibly slow.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] Designers planned to reduce code size with library routines to save and restore registers.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] RISC-V has no condition code register or carry bit.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] The designers believed that condition codes make fast CPUs more complex by forcing interactions between instructions in different stages of execution.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] This choice makes multiple-precision arithmetic more complex.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] Also, a few numerical tasks need more energy.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] As a result, predication (the conditional execution of instructions) is not supported.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] The designers claim that very fast, out-of-order CPU designs do predication anyway, by doing the comparison branch and conditional code in parallel, then discarding the unused path's effects.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] They also claim that even in simpler CPUs, predication is less valuable than branch prediction, which can prevent most stalls associated with conditional branches.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] Code without predication is larger, with more branches, but they also claim that a compressed instruction set (such as RISC-V's set *C*) solves that problem in most cases.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] Instead, RISC-V has short branches that perform comparisons: equal, not-equal, less-than, unsigned less-than, greater-than or equal and unsigned greater-than or equal.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] Ten comparison-branch operations are implemented with only six instructions, by reversing the order of operands in the assembler.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] For example, *branch if greater than* can be done by *less-than* with a reversed order of operands.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] The comparing branches have a twelve-bit signed range, and jump relative to the PC.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] Unlike some RISC architectures, RISC-V does not include a branch delay slot, a position after a branch instruction that can be filled with an instruction that is executed whether or not the branch is taken.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] RISC-V omits a branch delay slot because it complicates multicycle CPUs, superscalar CPUs, and long pipelines.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] Dynamic branch predictors have succeeded well enough to reduce the need for delayed branches.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] On the first encounter with a branch, RISC-V CPUs should assume that a negative relative branch (i.e. the sign bit of the offset is "1") will be taken.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] This assumes that a backward branch is a loop, and provides a default direction so that simple pipelined CPUs can fill their pipeline of instructions.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] Other than this, RISC-V does not require branch prediction, but core implementations are allowed to add it.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] RV32I reserves a "HINT" instruction space that presently does not contain any hints on branches; RV64I does the same.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] RISC-V segregates math into a minimal set of integer instructions (set *I*) with add, subtract, shift, bitwise logic and comparing-branches.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] These can simulate most of the other RISC-V instruction sets with software.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] The integer multiplication instructions (set *M*) include signed and unsigned multiply and divide.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] Double-precision integer multiplies and divides are included, as multiplies and divides that produce the *high word* of the result.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] The ISA document recommends that implementors of CPUs and compilers *fuse* a standardized sequence of high and low multiply and divide instructions to one operation if possible.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] The floating-point instructions (set *F*) include single-precision arithmetic and also comparison-branches similar to the integer arithmetic.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] It requires an additional set of 32 floating-point registers.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] These are separate from the integer registers.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] The double-precision floating point instructions (set *D*) generally assume that the floating-point registers are 64-bit (i.e., double-width), and the *F* subset is coordinated with the *D* set.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] A quad-precision 128-bit floating-point ISA (*Q*) is also defined.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] RISC-V computers without floating-point can use a floating-point software library.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] RISC-V does not cause exceptions on arithmetic errors, including overflow, underflow, subnormal, and divide by zero.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] Instead, both integer and floating-point arithmetic produce reasonable default values, and floating-point instructions set status bits.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] Divide-by-zero can be discovered by one branch after the division.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] The status bits can be tested by an operating system or periodic interrupt.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] RISC-V supports computers that share memory between multiple CPUs and threads.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] RISC-V's standard memory consistency model is release consistency.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] That is, loads and stores may generally be reordered, but some loads may be designated as *acquire* operations which must precede later memory accesses, and some stores may be designated as *release* operations which must follow earlier memory accesses.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] The base instruction set includes minimal support in the form of a `fence` instruction to enforce memory ordering.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] Although this is sufficient (`fence r, rw` provides *acquire* and `fence rw, w` provides *release*), combined operations can be more efficient.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] The atomic memory operation extension supports two types of atomic memory operations for release consistency.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] First, it provides general purpose *load-reserved* `lr` and *store-conditional* `sc` instructions.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] `lr` performs a load, and tries to reserve that address for its thread.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] A later store-conditional `sc` to the reserved address will be performed only if the reservation is not broken by an intervening store from another source.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] If the store succeeds, a zero is placed in a register.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] If it failed, a non-zero value indicates that software needs to retry the operation.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] In either case, the reservation is released.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] The second group of atomic instructions perform read-modify-write sequences: a load (which is optionally a load-acquire) to a destination register, then an operation between the loaded value and a source register, then a store of the result (which may optionally be a store-release).
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] Making the memory barriers optional permits combining the operations.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] The optional operations are enabled by *acquire* and *release* bits which are present in every atomic instruction.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] RISC-V defines nine possible operations: swap (use source register value directly); add; bitwise and, or, and exclusive-or; and signed and unsigned minimum and maximum.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] A system design may optimize these combined operations more than `lr` and `sc`.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] For example, if the destination register for a swap is the constant zero, the load may be skipped.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] If the value stored is unmodified since the load, the store may be skipped.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] However, a simple load-type instruction is usually performed before the `cas` to fetch the old value.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] The classic problem is that if a thread reads (loads) a value *A*, calculates a new value *C*, and then uses (`cas`) to replace *A* with *C*, it has no way to know whether concurrent activity in another thread has replaced *A* with some other value *B* and then restored the *A* in between.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] In some algorithms (e.g., ones in which the values in memory are pointers to dynamically allocated blocks), this ABA problem can lead to incorrect results.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] The most common solution employs a *double-wide `cas`* instruction to update both the pointer and an adjacent counter; unfortunately, such an instruction requires a special instruction format to specify multiple registers, performs several reads and writes, and can have complex bus operation.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] The `lr`/`sc` alternative is more efficient.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] It usually requires only one memory load, and minimizing slow memory operations is desirable.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] It's also exact: it controls all accesses to the memory cell, rather than just assuring a bit pattern.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] However, unlike `cas`, it can permit livelock, in which two or more threads repeatedly cause each other's instructions to fail.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] RISC-V guarantees forward progress (no livelock) if the code follows rules on the timing and sequence of instructions: 1) It must use only the *I* subset.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] 2) To prevent repetitive cache misses, the code (including the retry loop) must occupy no more than 16 consecutive instructions.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] 3) It must include no system or fence instructions, or taken backward branches between the `lr` and `sc`.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] 4) The backward branch to the retry loop must be to the original sequence.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] The specification gives an example of how to use the read-modify-write atomic instructions to lock a data structure.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] The standard RISC-V ISA specifies that all instructions are 32 bits.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] This makes for a particularly simple implementation, but like other RISC processors with 32-bit instruction encoding, results in larger code size than in instruction sets with variable-length instructions.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] To compensate, RISC-V's *32-bit* instructions are actually 30 bits; 3⁄4 of the opcode space is reserved for an optional (but recommended) variable-length *compressed* instruction set, RVC, that includes 16-bit instructions.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] As in SuperH, ARM Thumb, and MIPS16, the compressed instructions are simply alternative encodings for a subset of the larger instructions.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] Like SuperH, but unlike the ARM or MIPS compressed sets, space was reserved from the start so there is no separate operating mode.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] Standard and compressed instructions may be intermixed freely.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] Because (like Thumb-1 and MIPS16) the compressed instructions are simply alternate encodings (aliases) for a selected subset of larger instructions, the compression can be implemented in the assembler, and it is not essential for the compiler to even know about it.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] The prototype code was 20% smaller than an x86 PC and MIPS compressed code, and 2% larger than ARM Thumb-2 code.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] It also substantially reduced both the needed cache memory and the estimated power use of the memory system.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] The researcher intended to reduce the code's binary size for small computers, especially embedded computer systems.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] The prototype included 33 of the most frequently used instructions, recoded as compact 16-bit formats using operation codes previously reserved for the compressed set.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] The compression was done in the assembler, with no changes to the compiler.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] Compressed instructions omitted fields that are often zero, used small immediate values or accessed subsets (16 or 8) of the registers.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] `addi` is very common and often compressible.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] Much of the difference in size compared to ARM's Thumb set occurred because RISC-V, and the prototype, have no instructions to save and restore multiple registers.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] Instead, the compiler generated conventional instructions that access the stack.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] The prototype RVC assembler then often converted these to compressed forms that were half the size.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] However, this still took more code space than the ARM instructions that save and restore multiple registers.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] The researcher proposed to modify the compiler to call library routines to save and restore registers.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] These routines would tend to remain in a code cache and thus run fast, though probably not as fast as a save-multiple instruction.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] Standard RVC requires occasional use of 32-bit instructions.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] Several nonstandard RVC proposals are complete, requiring no 32-bit instructions, and are said to have higher densities than standard RVC.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] Another proposal builds on these, and claims to use less coding range as well.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] An instruction set for the smallest *embedded* CPUs (set E) is reduced in other ways: Only 16 of the 32 integer registers are supported.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] All current extensions may be used; a floating-point extension to use the integer registers for floating-point values is being considered.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] The privileged instruction set supports only machine mode, user mode and memory schemes that use base-and-bound address relocation.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] Discussion has occurred for a microcontroller profile for RISC-V, to ease development of deeply embedded systems.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] It centers on faster, simple C-language support for interrupts, simplified security modes and a simplified POSIX application binary interface.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] Correspondents have also proposed smaller, non-standard, 16-bit *RV16E* ISAs: Several serious proposals would use the 16-bit *C* instructions with 8 × 16-bit registers.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] An April fools' joke proposed a very practical arrangement: Utilize 16 × 16-bit integer registers, with the standard *EIMC* ISAs (including 32-bit instructions.) The joke was to use bank switching when a 32-bit CPU would be clearly superior with the larger address space.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] RISC-V's ISA includes a separate privileged instruction set specification, which mostly describes three privilege levels plus an orthogonal hypervisor mode.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] As of December 2021, version 1.12 is ratified by RISC-V International.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] Systems with machine-mode, supervisor mode (for operating system) and user-modes for typical operating systems.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] These correspond roughly to systems with up to four ‘’rings’’ of privilege and security, at most: machine, hypervisor, supervisor and user.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] Each layer also is expected to have a thin layer of standardized supporting software that communicates to a more-privileged layer, or hardware.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] The ISA also includes a hypervisor mode that is orthogonal to the user and supervisor modes.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] The basic feature is a configuration bit that either permits supervisor-level code to access hypervisor registers, or causes an interrupt on accesses.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] This bit lets supervisor mode directly handle the hardware needed by a hypervisor.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] This simplifies the implementation of hypervisors that are hosted by an operating system.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] This is a popular mode to run warehouse-scale computers.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] To support non-hosted hypervisors, the bit can cause these accesses to interrupt to a hypervisor.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] The design also simplifies nesting of hypervisors, in which a hypervisor runs under a hypervisor, and if necessary it lets the kernel use hypervisor features within its own kernel code.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] As a result, the hypervisor form of the ISA supports five modes: machine, supervisor, user, supervisor-under-hypervisor and user-under-supervisor.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] The privileged instruction set specification explicitly defines *hardware threads*, or *harts*.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] Multiple hardware threads are a common practice in more-capable computers.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] When one thread is stalled, waiting for memory, others can often proceed.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] Hardware threads can help make better use of the large number of registers and execution units in fast out-of-order CPUs.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] Finally, hardware threads can be a simple, powerful way to handle interrupts: No saving or restoring of registers is required, simply executing a different hardware thread.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] However, the only hardware thread required in a RISC-V computer is thread zero.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] Interrupts and exceptions are handled together.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] Exceptions are caused by instruction execution including illegal instructions and system calls, while interrupts are caused by external events.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] The existing control and status register definitions support RISC-V's error and memory exceptions, and a small number of interrupts, typically via an "advanced core local interruptor" (ACLINT).
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] For systems with more interrupts, the specification also defines a platform-level interrupt controller (PLIC) to coordinate large number of interrupts among multiple processors.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] Interrupts always start at the highest-privileged machine level, and the control registers of each level have explicit *forwarding* bits to route interrupts to less-privileged code.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] For example, the hypervisor need not include software that executes on each interrupt to forward an interrupt to an operating system.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] Instead, on set-up, it can set bits to forward the interrupt.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] Several memory systems are supported in the specification.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] Physical-only is suited to the simplest embedded systems.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] There are also four UNIX-style virtual memory systems for memory cached in mass-storage systems.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] The virtual memory systems support MMU with four sizes, with addresses sized 32, 39, 48 and 57 bits.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] All virtual memory systems support 4 KiB pages, multilevel page-table trees and use very similar algorithms to walk the page table trees.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] All are designed for either hardware or software page-table walking.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] To optionally reduce the cost of page table walks, super-sized pages may be leaf pages in higher levels of a system's page table tree.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] SV32 is only supported on 32-bit implementations, has a two-layer page table tree and supports 4 MiB superpages.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] SV39 has a three level page table, and supports 2 MiB superpages and 1 GiB gigapages.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] It also has a 4-level page table and supports 2 MiB superpages, 1 GiB gigapages, and 512 GiB terapages.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] SV57 has a 5-level page table and supports 2 MiB superpages, 1 GiB gigapages, 512 GiB terapages and 256 TiB petapages.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] Superpages are aligned on the page boundaries for the next-lowest size of page.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] Some bit-manipulation ISA extensions were ratified in November 2021 (Zba, Zbb, Zbc, Zbs).
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] The Zbs extension allows setting, getting, clearing, and toggling individual bits in a register by their index (bseti, bset, bexti, bext, bclri, bclr, binvi,binv).
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] The Zbc extension has instructions for "carryless multiplication", which does the multiplication of polynomials over the Galois field GF(2) (clmul, clmulh, clmulr).
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] These are useful for cryptography and CRC checks of data integrity.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] Done well, a more specialised bit-manipulation subset can aid cryptographic, graphic, and mathematical operations.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] The criteria for inclusion documented in the draft were compliant with RISC-V philosophies and ISA formats, substantial improvements in code density or speed (i.e., at least a 3-for-1 reduction in instructions), and substantial real-world applications, including preexisting compiler support.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] Version 0.93 of the bit-manipulation extension includes those instructions; some of them are now in version 1.0.1 of the scalar and entropy source instructions cryptography extension.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] Packed-SIMD instructions are widely used by commercial CPUs to inexpensively accelerate multimedia and other digital signal processing.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] For simple, cost-reduced RISC-V systems, the base ISA's specification proposed to use the floating-point registers' bits to perform parallel single instruction, multiple data (SIMD) sub-word arithmetic.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] In 2017 a vendor published a more detailed proposal to the mailing list, and this can be cited as version 0.1.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] As of 2019, the efficiency of this proposed ISA varies from 2x to 5x a base CPU for a variety of DSP codecs.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] The proposal lacked instruction formats and a license assignment to RISC-V International, but it was reviewed by the mailing list.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] Some unpopular parts of this proposal were that it added a condition code, the first in a RISC-V design, linked adjacent registers (also a first), and has a loop counter that can be difficult to implement in some microarchitectures.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] The proposed vector-processing instruction set may make the packed SIMD set obsolete.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] The designers hope to have enough flexibility that a CPU can implement vector instructions in a standard processor's registers.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] This would enable minimal implementations with similar performance to a multimedia ISA, as above.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] However, a true vector coprocessor could execute the same code with higher performance.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] As of 19 September 2021, the vector extension is at version 1.0.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] It is a conservative, flexible design of a general-purpose mixed-precision vector processor, suitable to execute compute kernels.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] Code would port easily to CPUs with differing vector lengths, ideally without recompiling.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] In contrast, short-vector SIMD extensions are less convenient.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] In these, a change in word-width forces a change to the instruction set to expand the vector registers (in the case of x86, from 64-bit MMX registers to 128-bit Streaming SIMD Extensions (SSE), to 256-bit Advanced Vector Extensions (AVX), and AVX-512).
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] The result is a growing instruction set, and a need to port working code to the new instructions.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] In the RISC-V vector ISA, rather than fix the vector length in the architecture, instructions (`vsetvli`, `vsetivli`, and `vsetvl`) are available which take a requested size and sets the vector length to the minimum of the hardware limit and the requested size.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] So, the RISC-V proposal is more like a Cray's long-vector design or ARM's Scalable Vector Extension.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] That is, each vector in up to 32 vectors is the same length.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] The application specifies the total vector width it requires, and the processor determines the vector length it can provide with available on-chip resources.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] This takes the form of an instruction (`vsetcfg`) with four immediate operands, specifying the number of vector registers of each available width needed.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] The total must be no more than the addressable limit of 32, but may be less if the application does not require them all.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] The vector length is limited by the available on-chip storage divided by the number of bytes of storage needed for each entry.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] Outside of vector loops, the application can zero the number of requested vector registers, saving the operating system the work of preserving them on context switches.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] The vector length is not only architecturally variable, but designed to vary at run time also.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] To achieve this flexibility, the instruction set is likely to use variable-width data paths and variable-type operations using polymorphic overloading.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] The plan is that these can reduce the size and complexity of the ISA and compiler.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] Recent experimental vector processors with variable-width data paths also show profitable increases in operations per: second (speed), area (lower cost), and watt (longer battery life).
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] Unlike a typical modern graphics processing unit, there are no plans to provide special hardware to support branch predication.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] Instead, lower cost compiler-based predication will be used.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] There is a preliminary specification for RISC-V's hardware-assisted debugger.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] The debugger will use a transport system such as Joint Test Action Group (JTAG) or Universal Serial Bus (USB) to access debug registers.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] A standard hardware debug interface may support either a *standardized abstract interface* or *instruction feeding*.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] As of January 2017, the exact form of the *abstract interface* remains undefined, but proposals include a memory mapped system with standardized addresses for the registers of debug devices or a command register and a data register accessible to the communication system.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] Correspondents claim that similar systems are used by Freescale's background debug mode interface (BDM) for some CPUs, ARM, OpenRISC, and Aeroflex's LEON.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] In *instruction feeding*, the CPU will process a debug exception to execute individual instructions written to a register.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] This may be supplemented with a data-passing register and a module to directly access the memory.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] Instruction feeding lets the debugger access the computer exactly as software would.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] It also minimizes changes in the CPU, and adapts to many types of CPU.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] This was said to be especially apt for RISC-V because it is designed explicitly for many types of computers.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] The data-passing register allows a debugger to write a data-movement loop to RAM, and then execute the loop to move data into or out of the computer at a speed near the maximum speed of the debug system's data channel.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] Correspondents say that similar systems are used by MIPS Technologies MIPS, Intel Quark, Tensilica's Xtensa, and for Freescale Power ISA CPUs' background debug mode interface (BDM).
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] A vendor proposed a hardware trace subsystem for standardization, donated a conforming design, and initiated a review.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] The proposal is for a hardware module that can trace code execution on most RISC-V CPUs.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] To reduce the data rate, and permit simpler or less-expensive paths for the trace data, the proposal does not generate trace data that can be calculated from a binary image of the code.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] It sends only data that indicates "uninferrable" paths through the program, such as which conditional branches are taken.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] To reduce the data rates, branches that can be calculated, such as unconditional branches, are not traced.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] The proposed interface between the module and the control unit is a logic signal for each uninferrable type of instruction.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] Addresses and other data are to be provided in a specialized bus attached to appropriate data sources in a CPU.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] The data structure sent to an external trace unit is a series of short messages with the needed data.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p02] The details of the data channel are intentionally not described in the proposal, because several are likely to make sense.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p03] The RISC-V organization maintains a list of RISC-V CPU and SoC implementations.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p03] Due to trade wars and possible sanctions that would prevent China from accessing proprietary ISAs, as of 2023 the country was planning to shift most of its CPU architectures and designs of microcontrollers (MCUs) to RISC-V cores.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p03] In 2023, the European Union was set to provide 270 million euros within a so-called Framework Partnership Agreement (FPA) to a single company that was able and willing to carry out a RISC-V CPU development project aimed at supercomputers, servers, and data centers.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p03] According to The Register, Chinese media reported in March 2025 from the conference where the server-grade CPU Alibaba DAMO Xuantie C930 was launched that senior Alibaba Cloud executives had predicted that RISC-V would become a mainstream cloud architecture as early as 2030.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p03] According to Reuters, Chinese government bodies in 2025 had been working on "guidance" that would promote widespread use of RISC-V throughout China.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p03] In 2019, SiFive of Santa Clara, California, announced their first RISC-V out-of-order high performance CPU core, the U8 Series Processor IP.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p03] SiFive was established specifically for developing RISC-V hardware and began releasing processor models in 2017.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p03] These included a quad-core, 64-bit (RV64GC) system on a chip (SoC) capable of running general-purpose operating systems such as Linux.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p03] In July 2019, DAMO Academy, the research arm of Alibaba Group of Hangzhou, China, announced the 2.5 GHz 16-core 64-bit (RV64GC) Xuantie 910 out-of-order processor.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p03] In October 2021 the Xuantie 910 was released as an open-source design.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p03] In 2022, Imagination Technologies of Kings Langley, England, announced it had paired its own 64bit Catapult RISC-V core, with its IMG BXE-2-32 GPU, on a SoC, that was validated by Andes Technology.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p03] The BXE GPU supporting Vulkan 1.2, OpenGL ES 3.x/2.0/1.1, OpenCL 3.0, and Android NN HAL APIs.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p03] In November 2023, DAMO unveiled three updated processors: the Xuantie C920, Xuantie C907 and Xuantie R910; these processors were aimed at a variety of application areas, including autonomous vehicles, artificial intelligence (AI), enterprise hard drives, and network communications.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p03] The processor is based on the X60 core design, integrates an Imagination Technologies IMG BXE-2-32 graphics unit, and supports the vector extension RVV 1.0.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p03] In January 2025, SpacemiT announced the development of a server processor with up to 64 RISC-V cores, called "VitalStone V100" and made with a 12 nm-class process technology.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p03] The VitalStone V100 processor is largely based on the OpenC910 project design, a design which is modelled on the Xuantie C910 processor, designed by Alibaba's DAMO Academy.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p03] In March 2025, Alibaba's DAMO Academy launched the server-grade Xuantie C930 core, which supported the next-generation RVA23 profile family, required by Ubuntu Linux from October 2025.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p03] The C930 CPU core was advertised as ideal for servers, personal computers, and autonomous cars.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p03] It created significant competition for the California-based company SiFive and its P870 core, the design of which SiFive had already released in October 2023.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p03] The P870 was the first SiFive core to support the new RVA23 profile family.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p03] Both with regard to the C930 and the P870 design, no physical chips had actually been built for general sale in August 2025, however.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p03] On 26 March 2026, Alibaba released the Xuantie C950, a high-performance 64-bit RISC-V processor core.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p03] This core, which was built on the up-to-date RVA23 profile, was designed for high workloads such as edge AI, cloud computing, and other high-performance systems.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p03] The C950 had a maximum clock frequency of 3.2 GHz and was ready for production on an advanced 5-nm process node, with sources indicating that TSMC would manufacture the C950.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p03] Industry magazine *EE Times* commented that the C950’s performance benchmarks proved that an open-source design could reach performance levels that, up to 2026, only proprietary designs from Intel or Arm were able to reach.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p03] In 2022, ClockworkPi released two hobbyist computing kits, the DevTerm terminal and uConsole handheld computer.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p03] Both kits offered a single core 64-bit RISC-V module as an option, using the RV64IMAFDCVU based on the Allwinner D1 SoC.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p03] The device's basic model, available from Alibaba, was still expensive at roughly US$1500 considering it was powered by the relatively slow Alibaba (DAMO) CPU "XuanTie C910".
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p03] An upgrade in June 2024 doubled the core count to 8 cores and increased the clock speed to 2 GHz (from 1.5 GHz), while dropping the price to US$1,000.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p03] The processor used was a SpacemiT SoC K1.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p03] A collaboration with Canonical meant that the ROMA II came pre-installed with the major international Linux distribution Ubuntu.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p03] In 2024, DeepComputing announced a collaboration with Framework Computer to produce a mainboard for its Framework Laptop 13.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p03] On 4 February 2025 the laptop was ready to ship; it was mainly targeted at developers.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p03] It features a 4-core StarFive JH7110 processor.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p03] In 2025, DeepComputing announced DC-ROMA AI PC, a second mainboard for the Framework Laptop 13.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p03] Its based on ESWIN's EIC7702X SoC that has AI capabilities up to 50 TOPS when NPU (Neural Processing Unit) is enabled.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p03] In addition to having a large number of CPU hardware designs, RISC-V is also supported by toolchains, operating systems (e.g.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p03] Available RISC-V software tools include a GNU Compiler Collection (GCC) toolchain (with GDB, the debugger), an LLVM toolchain, the OVPsim simulator (and library of RISC-V Fast Processor Models), the Spike simulator, and a simulator in QEMU (RV32GC/RV64GC).
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p03] A port of OpenJDK is already integrated into the mainline OpenJDK repository.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p03] Operating system support exists for the Linux kernel, FreeBSD, NetBSD, and OpenBSD.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p03] The preliminary FreeBSD port to the RISC-V architecture was upstreamed in February 2016, and shipped in FreeBSD 11.0.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p03] As one of only seven CPU architectures (e.g.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p03] ARM or x86), Debian Linux has officially supported RISC-V since Debian Trixie, which was released in August 2025.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p03] Ports of Linux distributions Fedora, and openSUSE, and a port of Haiku, also exist (64-bit versions only, not 32-bit versions).
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p03] In June 2024, Hong Kong company DeepComputing announced the commercial availability of the first RISC-V laptop in the world to run the popular Linux operating system Ubuntu in its standard form ("out of the box").
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p03] In August 2025, Ubuntu decided, however, to drop support for older "profiles" (e.g.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p03] RV64GC or RVA20), meaning then-existing RISC-V CPUs were no longer supported from Ubuntu version 25.10 (i.e. from October 2025; older Ubuntu versions still supported older profiles and CPUs, of course).
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p03] In September 2025, there were no actual processors to be had on the market for the "RVA23" profile newly required by Ubuntu, only a couple of designs (e.g. the XuanTie C930 from DAMO Academy, or the SiFive P870).
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p03] UEFI Spec v2.7 has defined the RISC-V binding and a TianoCore port has been done by HPE engineers and is expected to be upstreamed.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p03] A RISC-V boot deep dive was done as part of openSUSE Hackweek 20.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p03] There is a port of the seL4 microkernel with functional correctness, integrity and information flow properties formally verified.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p03] Hex Five released the first Secure IoT Stack for RISC-V with FreeRTOS support.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p03] Also xv6, a modern reimplementation of Sixth Edition Unix in ANSI C used for pedagogical purposes in MIT, was ported.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p03] Pharos RTOS has been ported to 64-bit RISC-V (including time and memory protection).
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p03] *Also see* Comparison of real-time operating systems.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p03] A simulator exists to run a RISC-V Linux system on a web browser using JavaScript.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p03] QEMU supports running (using binary translation) 32- and 64-bit RISC-V systems (e.g.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p03] Linux) with many emulated or virtualized devices (serial, parallel, USB, network, storage, real time clock, watchdog, audio), as well as running RISC-V Linux binaries (translating syscalls to the host kernel).
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p03] It does support multi-core emulation (SMP).
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p03] The CREATOR simulator is portable and allows the user to learn various assembly languages of different processors (CREATOR has examples with an implementation of RISC-V and MIPS32 instructions).
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p03] The RISC-V International Compliance Task Group has a GitHub repository for RV32IMC.
[src:chisel-hdl/risc-v-p03] The extensible educational simulator WepSIM implements a microprogrammed subset of RISC-V instructions (RV32I+M) and allows the execution of subroutines on both, at assembly and microprogramming level.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] Scala source code can be compiled to JVM bytecode and run on a Java virtual machine (JVM).
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] Scala can also be transpiled to JavaScript to run in a browser, or compiled directly to a native executable using Clang.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] When running on the JVM, Scala provides language interoperability with Java so that libraries written in either language may be referenced directly in Scala or Java code.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] Like Java, Scala is object-oriented, and uses a syntax termed *curly-brace* which is similar to the language C.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] Since Scala 3, there is also an option to use the off-side rule (indenting) to structure blocks, and its use is advised.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] Martin Odersky has said that this turned out to be the most productive change introduced in Scala 3.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] Unlike Java, Scala has many features of functional programming languages (like Scheme, Standard ML, and Haskell), including currying, immutability, lazy evaluation, and pattern matching.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] The name Scala is a portmanteau of *scalable* and *language*, signifying that it is designed to grow with the demands of its users.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] The design of Scala started in 2001 at the École Polytechnique Fédérale de Lausanne (EPFL) (in Lausanne, Switzerland) by Martin Odersky.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] It followed on from work on Funnel, a programming language combining ideas from functional programming and Petri nets.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] Odersky formerly worked on Generic Java, and javac, Sun's Java compiler.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] After an internal release in late 2003, Scala was released publicly in early 2004 on the Java platform, A second version (v2.0) followed in March 2006.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] On 17 January 2011, the Scala team won a five-year research grant of over €2.3 million from the European Research Council.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] On 12 May 2011, Odersky and collaborators launched Typesafe Inc.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] (later renamed Lightbend Inc.), a company to provide commercial support, training, and services for Scala.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] Typesafe received a $3 million investment in 2011 from Greylock Partners.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] Scala runs on the Java platform (Java virtual machine) and is compatible with existing Java programs.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] The reference Scala software distribution, including compiler and libraries, is released under the Apache license.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] Scala Native is a Scala compiler that targets the LLVM compiler infrastructure to create executable code that uses a lightweight managed runtime, which uses the Boehm garbage collector.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] The project is led by Denys Shabalin and had its first release, 0.1, on 14 March 2017.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] Development of Scala Native began in 2015 with a goal of being faster than just-in-time compilation for the JVM by eliminating the initial runtime compilation of code and also providing the ability to call native routines directly.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] A reference Scala compiler targeting the .NET Framework and its Common Language Runtime was released in June 2004, but was officially dropped in 2012.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] Unlike the stand-alone Hello World application for Java, there is no class declaration and nothing is declared to be static.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] This is analogous to the process for compiling and running Java code.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] Indeed, Scala's compiling and executing model is identical to that of Java, making it compatible with Java build tools such as Apache Ant.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] Scala includes an interactive shell and scripting support.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] The following example shows the differences between Java and Scala syntax.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] These syntactic relaxations are designed to allow support for domain-specific languages.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] The following example contrasts the definition of classes in Java and Scala.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] Scala has the same compiling model as Java and C#, namely separate compiling and dynamic class loading, so that Scala code can call Java libraries.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] Scala's operational characteristics are the same as Java's.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] The Scala compiler generates byte code that is nearly identical to that generated by the Java compiler.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] In fact, Scala code can be decompiled to readable Java code, with the exception of certain constructor operations.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] To the Java virtual machine (JVM), Scala code and Java code are indistinguishable.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] The only difference is one extra runtime library, `scala-library.jar`.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] Scala adds a large number of features compared with Java, and has some fundamental differences in its underlying model of expressions and types, which make the language theoretically cleaner and eliminate several *corner cases* in Java.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] From the Scala perspective, this is practically important because several added features in Scala are also available in C#.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] As mentioned above, Scala has a good deal of syntactic flexibility, compared with Java.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] By themselves, these may seem like questionable choices, but collectively they serve the purpose of allowing domain-specific languages to be defined in Scala without needing to extend the compiler.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] For example, Erlang's special syntax for sending a message to an actor, i.e.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] `actor ! message` can be (and is) implemented in a Scala library without needing language extensions.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] Java makes a sharp distinction between primitive types (e.g.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] `int` and `boolean`) and reference types (any class).
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] Only reference types are part of the inheritance scheme, deriving from `java.lang.Object`.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] In Scala, all types inherit from a top-level class `Any`, whose immediate children are `AnyVal` (value types, such as `Int` and `Boolean`) and `AnyRef` (reference types, as in Java).
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] This means that the Java distinction between primitive types and boxed types (e.g.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] `Integer`) is not present in Scala; boxing and unboxing is completely transparent to the user.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] Scala 2.10 allows for new value types to be defined by the user.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] Instead of the Java "foreach" loops for looping through an iterator, Scala has `for`-expressions, which are similar to list comprehensions in languages such as Haskell, or a combination of list comprehensions and generator expressions in Python.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] For-expressions using the `yield` keyword allow a new collection to be generated by iterating over an existing one, returning a new collection of the same type.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] They are translated by the compiler into a series of `map`, `flatMap` and `filter` calls.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] Where `yield` is not used, the code approximates to an imperative-style loop, by translating to `foreach`.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] (The expression `1 to 25` is not special syntax.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] Expression `(mention, times) <- mentions` is an example of pattern matching (see below).
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] Iterating over a map returns a set of key-value tuples, and pattern-matching allows the tuples to easily be destructured into separate variables for the key and value.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] Similarly, the result of the comprehension also returns key-value tuples, which are automatically built back up into a map because the source object (from the variable `mentions`) is a map.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] If `mentions` instead held a list, set, array or other collection of tuples, exactly the same code above would yield a new collection of the same type.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] While supporting all of the object-oriented features available in Java (and in fact, augmenting them in various ways), Scala also provides a large number of capabilities that are normally found only in functional programming languages.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] Together, these features allow Scala programs to be written in an almost completely functional style and also allow functional and object-oriented styles to be mixed.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] Unlike C or Java, but similar to languages such as Lisp, Scala makes no distinction between statements and expressions.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] All statements are in fact expressions that evaluate to some value.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] Functions that would be declared as returning `void` in C or Java, and statements like `while` that logically do not return a value, are in Scala considered to return the type `Unit`, which is a singleton type, with only one object of that type.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] Functions and operators that never return at all (e.g. the `throw` operator or a function that always exits non-locally using an exception) logically have return type `Nothing`, a special type containing no objects; that is, a bottom type, i.e. a subclass of every possible type.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] Similarly, an `if-then-else` "statement" is actually an expression, which produces a value, i.e. the result of evaluating one of the two branches.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] For similar reasons, `return` statements are unnecessary in Scala, and in fact are discouraged.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] As in Lisp, the last expression in a block of code is the value of that block of code, and if the block of code is the body of a function, it will be returned by the function.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] Due to type inference, the type of variables, function return values, and many other expressions can typically be omitted, as the compiler can deduce it.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] Examples are `val x = "foo"` (for an immutable constant or immutable object) or `var x = 1.5` (for a variable whose value can later be changed).
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] Type inference in Scala is essentially local, in contrast to the more global Hindley-Milner algorithm used in Haskell, ML and other more purely functional languages.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] This is done to facilitate object-oriented programming.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] The result is that certain types still need to be declared (most notably, function parameters, and the return types of recursive functions), e.g.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] In Scala, functions are objects, and a convenient syntax exists for specifying anonymous functions.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] An example is the expression `x => x < 2`, which specifies a function with one parameter, that compares its argument to see if it is less than 2.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] It is equivalent to the Lisp form `(lambda (x) (< x 2))`.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] Neither the type of x nor the return type need be explicitly specified, and can generally be inferred by type inference; but they can be explicitly specified, e.g., as `(x: Int) => x < 2` or even `(x: Int) => (x < 2): Boolean`.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] Anonymous functions behave as true closures in that they automatically capture any variables that are lexically available in the environment of the enclosing function.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] Those variables will be available even after the enclosing function returns, and unlike in the case of Java's *anonymous inner classes* do not need to be declared as final.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] Scala enforces a distinction between immutable and mutable variables.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] Mutable variables are declared using the `var` keyword and immutable values are declared using the `val` keyword.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] A variable declared using the `val` keyword cannot be reassigned in the same way that a variable declared using the `final` keyword can't be reassigned in Java.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] `val`s are only shallowly immutable, that is, an object referenced by a val is not guaranteed to itself be immutable.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] Immutable classes are encouraged by convention however, and the Scala standard library provides a rich set of immutable collection classes.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] Scala provides mutable and immutable variants of most collection classes, and the immutable version is always used unless the mutable version is explicitly imported.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] The immutable variants are persistent data structures that always return an updated copy of an old object instead of updating the old object destructively in place.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] An example of this is immutable linked lists where prepending an element to a list is done by returning a new list node consisting of the element and a reference to the list tail.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] Appending an element to a list can only be done by prepending all elements in the old list to a new list with only the new element.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] In the same way, inserting an element in the middle of a list will copy the first half of the list, but keep a reference to the second half of the list.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] This allows for very easy concurrency — no locks are needed as no shared objects are ever modified.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] Evaluation is strict ("eager") by default.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] In other words, Scala evaluates expressions as soon as they are available, rather than as needed.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] However, it is possible to declare a variable non-strict ("lazy") with the `lazy` keyword, meaning that the code to produce the variable's value will not be evaluated until the first time the variable is referenced.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] Non-strict collections of various types also exist (such as the type `Stream`, a non-strict linked list), and any collection can be made non-strict with the `view` method.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] Non-strict collections provide a good semantic fit to things like server-produced data, where the evaluation of the code to generate later elements of a list (that in turn triggers a request to a server, possibly located somewhere else on the web) only happens when the elements are actually needed.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] Functional programming languages commonly provide tail call optimization to allow for extensive use of recursion without stack overflow problems.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] Limitations in JVM bytecode complicate tail call optimization on the JVM.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] In general, a function that calls itself with a tail call can be optimized, but mutually recursive functions cannot.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] Trampolines have been suggested as a workaround.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] Trampoline support has been provided by the Scala library with the object `scala.util.control.TailCalls` since Scala 2.8.0 (released 14 July 2010).
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] A function may optionally be annotated with `@tailrec`, in which case it will not compile unless it is tail recursive.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] An example of this optimization could be implemented using the factorial definition.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] This ensures tail call optimization and thus prevents a stack overflow error.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] Scala has built-in support for pattern matching, which can be thought of as a more sophisticated, extensible version of a switch statement, where arbitrary data types can be matched (rather than just simple types like integers, Booleans and strings), including arbitrary nesting.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] A special type of class known as a *case class* is provided, which includes automatic support for pattern matching and can be used to model the algebraic data types used in many functional programming languages.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] The idea here is that we partition a list into the elements less than a pivot and the elements not less, recursively sort each part, and paste the results together with the pivot in between.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] This uses the same divide-and-conquer strategy of mergesort and other fast sorting algorithms.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] The `match` operator is used to do pattern matching on the object stored in `list`.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] Each `case` expression is tried in turn to see if it will match, and the first match determines the result.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] In this case, `Nil` only matches the literal object `Nil`, but `pivot :: tail` matches a non-empty list, and simultaneously *destructures* the list according to the pattern given.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] In this case, the associated code will have access to a local variable named `pivot` holding the head of the list, and another variable `tail` holding the tail of the list.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] These variables are read-only, and are semantically very similar to variable bindings established using the `let` operator in Lisp and Scheme.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] Pattern matching also happens in local variable declarations.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] In this case, the return value of the call to `tail.partition` is a tuple — in this case, two lists.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] (Tuples differ from other types of containers, e.g. lists, in that they are always of fixed size and the elements can be of differing types — although here they are both the same.) Pattern matching is the easiest way of fetching the two parts of the tuple.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] The form `_ < pivot` is a declaration of an anonymous function with a placeholder variable; see the section above on anonymous functions.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] The list operators `::` (which adds an element onto the beginning of a list, similar to `cons` in Lisp and Scheme) and `:::` (which appends two lists together, similar to `append` in Lisp and Scheme) both appear.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] Despite appearances, there is nothing "built-in" about either of these operators.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] As specified above, any string of symbols can serve as function name, and a method applied to an object can be written "infix"-style without the period or parentheses.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] In the pattern-matching example above, the body of the `match` operator is a partial function, which consists of a series of `case` expressions, with the first matching expression prevailing, similar to the body of a switch statement.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] Finally, a partial function can be used alone, and the result of calling it is equivalent to doing a `match` over it.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] Here a read-only *variable* is declared whose type is a function from lists of integers to lists of integers, and bind it to a partial function.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] Scala is a pure object-oriented language in the sense that every value is an object.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] Data types and behaviors of objects are described by classes and traits.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] Class abstractions are extended by subclassing and by a flexible mixin-based composition mechanism to avoid the problems of multiple inheritance.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] Traits are Scala's replacement for Java's interfaces.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] Interfaces in Java versions under 8 are highly restricted, able only to contain abstract function declarations.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] This has led to criticism that providing convenience methods in interfaces is awkward (the same methods must be reimplemented in every implementation), and extending a published interface in a backwards-compatible way is impossible.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] Traits are similar to mixin classes in that they have nearly all the power of a regular abstract class, lacking only class parameters (Scala's equivalent to Java's constructor parameters), since traits are always mixed in with a class.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] The `super` operator behaves specially in traits, allowing traits to be chained using composition in addition to inheritance.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] In other words, the call to `draw` first executed the code in `TitleDecoration` (the last trait mixed in), then (through the `super()` calls) threaded back through the other mixed-in traits and eventually to the code in `Window`, *even though none of the traits inherited from one another*.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] This is similar to the decorator pattern, but is more concise and less error-prone, as it doesn't require explicitly encapsulating the parent window, explicitly forwarding functions whose implementation isn't changed, or relying on run-time initialization of entity relationships.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] In other languages, a similar effect could be achieved at compile-time with a long linear chain of implementation inheritance, but with the disadvantage compared to Scala that one linear inheritance chain would have to be declared for each possible combination of the mix-ins.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] Scala is equipped with an expressive static type system that mostly enforces the safe and coherent use of abstractions.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] This makes most static type declarations optional.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] Static types need not be explicitly declared unless a compiler error indicates the need.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] In practice, some static type declarations are included for the sake of code clarity.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] A common technique in Scala, known as "enrich my library" (originally termed "pimp my library" by Martin Odersky in 2006; concerns were raised about this phrasing due to its negative connotations and immaturity), allows new methods to be used as if they were added to existing types.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] This is similar to the C# concept of extension methods but more powerful, because the technique is not limited to adding methods and can, for instance, be used to implement new interfaces.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] In Scala, this technique involves declaring an implicit conversion from the type "receiving" the method to a new type (typically, a class) that wraps the original type and provides the additional method.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] If a method cannot be found for a given type, the compiler automatically searches for any applicable implicit conversions to types that provide the method in question.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] This technique allows new methods to be added to an existing class using an add-on library such that only code that *imports* the add-on library gets the new functionality, and all other code is unaffected.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] Importing the members of `MyExtensions` brings the implicit conversion to extension class `IntPredicates` into scope.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] Scala's standard library includes support for futures and promises, in addition to the standard Java concurrency APIs.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] Originally, it also included support for the actor model, which is now available as a separate source-available platform Akka licensed by Lightbend Inc.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] Akka actors may be distributed or combined with software transactional memory (*transactors*).
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] Alternative communicating sequential processes (CSP) implementations for channel-based message passing are Communicating Scala Objects, or simply via JCSP.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] An Actor is like a thread instance with a mailbox.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] It can be created by `system.actorOf`, overriding the `receive` method to receive messages and using the `!` (exclamation point) method to send a message.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] The following example shows an EchoServer that can receive messages and then print them.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] Scala also comes with built-in support for data-parallel programming in the form of Parallel Collections integrated into its Standard Library since version 2.9.0.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] The following example shows how to use Parallel Collections to improve performance.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] Besides futures and promises, actor support, and data parallelism, Scala also supports asynchronous programming with software transactional memory, and event streams.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] The most well-known open-source cluster-computing solution written in Scala is Apache Spark.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] Additionally, Apache Kafka, the publish–subscribe message queue popular with Spark and other stream processing technologies, is written in Scala.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] There are several ways to test code in Scala.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] ScalaTest supports multiple testing styles and can integrate with Java-based testing frameworks.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] ScalaCheck is a library similar to Haskell's QuickCheck. specs2 is a library for writing executable software specifications.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] ScalaMock provides support for testing high-order and curried functions.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p01] JUnit and TestNG are popular testing frameworks written in Java.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p02] Scala is often compared with Groovy and Clojure, two other programming languages also using the JVM.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p02] Substantial differences between these languages exist in the type system, in the extent to which each language supports object-oriented and functional programming, and in the similarity of their syntax to that of Java.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p02] Scala is statically typed, while both Groovy and Clojure are dynamically typed.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p02] This makes the type system more complex and difficult to understand but allows almost all type errors to be caught at compile-time and can result in significantly faster execution.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p02] By contrast, dynamic typing requires more testing to ensure program correctness, and thus is generally slower, to allow greater programming flexibility and simplicity.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p02] Regarding speed differences, current versions of Groovy and Clojure allow optional type annotations to help programs avoid the overhead of dynamic typing in cases where types are practically static.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p02] This overhead is further reduced when using recent versions of the JVM, which has been enhanced with an *invoke dynamic* instruction for methods that are defined with dynamically typed arguments.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p02] These advances reduce the speed gap between static and dynamic typing, although a statically typed language, like Scala, is still the preferred choice when execution efficiency is very important.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p02] Regarding programming paradigms, Scala inherits the object-oriented model of Java and extends it in various ways.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p02] Groovy, while also strongly object-oriented, is more focused in reducing verbosity.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p02] In Clojure, object-oriented programming is deemphasised with functional programming being the main strength of the language.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p02] Scala also has many functional programming facilities, including features found in advanced functional languages like Haskell, and tries to be agnostic between the two paradigms, letting the developer choose between the two paradigms or, more frequently, some combination thereof.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p02] Regarding syntax similarity with Java, Scala inherits much of Java's syntax, as is the case with Groovy.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p02] Clojure on the other hand follows the Lisp syntax, which is different in both appearance and philosophy.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p02] Back in 2013, when Scala was in version 2.10, the ThoughtWorks Technology Radar, which is an opinion based biannual report of a group of senior technologists, recommended Scala adoption in its languages and frameworks category.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p02] In the 2018 edition of the *State of Java* survey, which collected data from 5160 developers on various Java-related topics, Scala places third in terms of use of alternative languages on the JVM.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p02] Relative to the prior year's edition of the survey, Scala's use among alternative JVM languages fell from 28.4% to 21.5%, overtaken by Kotlin, which rose from 11.4% in 2017 to 28.8% in 2018.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p02] The Popularity of Programming Language Index, which tracks searches for language tutorials, ranked Scala 15th in April 2018 with a small downward trend, and 17th in Jan 2021.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p02] This makes Scala the 3rd most popular JVM-based language after Java and Kotlin, ranked 12th.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p02] The RedMonk Programming Language Rankings, which establishes rankings based on the number of GitHub projects and questions asked on Stack Overflow, in January 2021 ranked Scala 14th.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p02] Here, Scala was placed inside a second-tier group of languages–ahead of Go, PowerShell, and Haskell, and behind Swift, Objective-C, TypeScript, and R.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p02] The TIOBE index of programming language popularity employs internet search engine rankings and similar publication counting to determine language popularity.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p02] In September 2021, it showed Scala in 31st place.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p02] In this ranking, Scala was ahead of Haskell (38th) and Erlang, but below Go (14th), Swift (15th), and Perl (19th).
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p02] As of 2022, JVM-based languages such as Clojure, Groovy, and Scala are highly ranked, but still significantly less popular than the original Java language, which is usually ranked in the top three places.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p02] In November 2011, Yammer moved away from Scala for reasons that included the learning curve for new team members and incompatibility from one version of the Scala compiler to the next.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p02] In March 2015, former VP of the Platform Engineering group at Twitter Raffi Krikorian, stated that he would not have chosen Scala in 2011 due to its learning curve.
[src:chisel-hdl/scala-programming-language-p02] The same month, LinkedIn SVP Kevin Scott stated their decision to "minimize [their] dependence on Scala".
